course_aims:
This course aims to develop entrepreneurs and entrepreneurship by introducing students to the theory, practice and research needed to start and grow new ventures, by:

exploring the key concepts of Entrepreneurship to navigate uncertainty & generate testable assumptions;

designing innovative business models to both deliver and capture value;

practice in developing & presenting new business ideas and analysing existing & emerging entrepreneurial firms;

create competitive advantage through venture formation, market analysis and entrepreneurial strategy; and

building confidence in students so to act on their entrepreneurial ambitions.

assessment_details.task_description:
The second presentation requires each team to pitch a map of their key assumptions underpinning the value of their business idea, along with how they intend to test these assumptions, to a small audience and to field questions based on that program. Each team will undergo two rounds, to two separate audience groups marked by two different facilitators. The focus rests on the assumptions that underpin the search phase of the lean startup process, where customers are discovered and validated. While this pitch may also pose early assumptions for the execution phase covering customer creation and company building, these execution elements are intended to be fully covered in the presentation of the Opportunity Appraisal in Session 12, and detailed in the Business Opportunity Appraisal Report.

The pitch will be delivered as a 5 minute presentation followed by 10 minutes of questions, moderated by the facilitator. The assumptions pitch allows each group to show the experiments they intend to conduct to generate new information as they navigate uncertainty in managing growth in line with strategic objectives. The assumptions pitch should map the discovery-driven pathway:

Define success - a clear expression of what you are aiming for with your team project;

Reverse financial statement - a very brief set of numbers that underpin your assumptions;

Operational needs - clear expression of key operational components to realise the reverse finances;

Critical Assumptions - what needs to prove true to meet your success horizon and what you will do if these assumptions prove to be not true;

Milestone checklist - the priorities you intend to apply to your executions, as you roll out this project, and how milestone priorities may change if assumptions are disproven

Each round of the the assumptions pitch needs to be succinct and capture interest from the selected audience. The facilitator will assign marks to the presenting group against the discovery-driven pathway outlined above, which will be averaged across the two rounds for a total of 10 marks, moderated by the peer assessment factor. Facilitators will indicate areas that need to be developed between the first and second round and then in preparation for the final Opportunity Appraisal (Session 12).
